Dear Recipients,

We are writing to inform you of a significant escalation in corporate intimidation tactics following our international accountability campaign concerning sexual violence at Dongguk University's Graduate School of Digital Image and Contents. This correspondence provides complete context for recipients who may be encountering this case for the first time, as well as documentation of the latest corporate retaliation attempts.

BACKGROUND: SEXUAL VIOLENCE CRISIS AND INTERNATIONAL EXPOSURE

Our organization has been documenting systematic sexual violence at Dongguk University's film program, where foreign women students have been subjected to predatory behavior by faculty and industry partners. After 47 days of complete silence from Korean authorities despite formal reports to prosecutors, police, and government agencies, our campaign went viral on Chinese social media platform Xiaohongshu, reaching over 20,000 viewers and triggering international attention.

The viral exposure revealed a disturbing pattern of institutional cover-up involving Dongguk University and its corporate partner Sidus Corporation, a Korean film production company that shares facilities with the university. According to Dongguk University's own official website, archived on April 14, 2025, "The department is located in the building, so-called 'Choong-Moo-Ro Yeong-Sang Center,' in which Sidus FNH, one of the top five film production companies in Korea, is based." This facility-sharing arrangement has created opportunities for systematic exploitation of vulnerable foreign students seeking industry connections.

ESCALATED LEGAL THREAT RECEIVED

On May 27, 2025, we received an escalated legal threat from Law Firm Shinwon (법무법인(유한)신원) on official letterhead, representing Sidus Corporation. The Korean legal threat, sent by Attorney Baek Kyung-tae, stated: "We are representing our client Sidus Corporation, and regarding the content related to Dongguk University's Graduate School of Digital Image and Contents that your organization sent yesterday, we assert that it is false information. We have prepared and are sending you the attached notice requesting your organization to send an apology letter accordingly."

This legal threat represents a significant escalation from previous corporate email intimidation to formal legal representation with official letterhead, PDF attachments, and confidentiality warnings. The law firm's contact information includes offices at 4th & 5th Floor, Hub One Building, 33 Seocho-daero 48-gil, Seocho-gu, Seoul 06645, with Attorney Baek Kyung-tae reachable at ktpaek@lawsw.co.kr.

CORPORATE RESPONSE ESCALATION ANALYSIS

This escalated legal threat demonstrates significant institutional concern for several critical reasons. First, Sidus retained external legal counsel within 24 hours of international exposure, indicating extreme urgency and institutional panic. The official letterhead correspondence represents an escalated institutional response far beyond typical corporate communications, while the formal legal process suggests serious concern regarding potential investigation outcomes.

Document analysis of the PDF threat reveals several concerning elements that suggest expedited rather than careful legal preparation. The metadata shows anonymous authorship identified only as "20200609l" rather than proper attorney identification, rushed production with a 24-hour turnaround from international exposure, outdated software from 2008-era PDF creation tools, and professional standards questions regarding anonymous legal threats. These elements suggest panic-driven document production rather than careful legal analysis.

The escalated legal response indicates significant institutional concern regarding potential investigation outcomes. Several contextual factors explain the urgency of this corporate legal intervention, particularly changes in the business environment that have undermined Sidus's previous operational advantages.

INDUSTRY CONTEXT AND CORPORATE DECLINE

The changing business environment has fundamentally altered the dynamics that previously enabled predatory behavior. Facility conditions may no longer support previous operational models, while industry transformation has altered traditional business relationships. Most significantly, corporate status decline means Sidus is no longer a "top five film production company in Korea," potentially due to misallocated institutional priorities during critical industry transitions such as streaming platform adoption.

Enhanced student awareness since MeToo 2018, when many cases of sexual violence in academia and the Korean film industry surfaced, has created a contemporary accountability environment that makes traditional predatory approaches far less effective. The Korean film industry restructuring has put traditional business models under review, while digital media transformation has made conventional distribution channels evolving. Post-MeToo institutional awareness has enhanced recognition of inappropriate conduct, and international oversight mechanisms have created global accountability frameworks.

POTENTIAL INVESTIGATION CONCERNS

The corporate legal response suggests awareness of serious vulnerabilities that investigation might reveal. Student testimonies regarding institutional promises and outcomes could expose systematic patterns of exploitation using false industry connections. Witness accounts of institutional communication patterns might document escalating intimidation when initial approaches failed. Evidence of institutional response to accountability measures could reveal cover-up attempts, while pattern documentation of systematic institutional behavior might establish criminal conspiracy.

The contemporary institutional context creates additional pressure points for investigation. Public awareness of industry transformation and institutional relevance has undermined previous leverage tactics. Facility conditions and operational capacity documentation could reveal the gap between promises and reality. International oversight has created accountability pressure that makes traditional cover-up approaches ineffective.

INVESTIGATION SCOPE AND CRIMINAL EXPOSURE

A comprehensive investigation would examine systematic institutional interactions using industry partnership claims to exploit vulnerable students. Institutional response patterns when accountability measures were implemented could reveal obstruction and retaliation. University partnership arrangements and access protocols might expose how the facility-sharing relationship enabled predatory access. Multiple witness testimonies regarding institutional communication could establish patterns of criminal behavior, while institutional adaptation to changing accountability environments might reveal consciousness of guilt.

Investigation considerations would include student testimonies regarding institutional promises and outcomes, which could expose the gap between industry connection claims and reality. Institutional communication patterns with documented witness accounts might reveal escalating threats when manipulation failed. Corporate operational context within industry transformation could explain desperation driving criminal behavior, while university partnership protocols and institutional access arrangements might expose systematic enabling of predatory conduct.

INSTITUTIONAL RESPONSE PATTERNS AND STRATEGIC TRAP

Sidus Corporation finds itself caught in a strategic trap where every response option creates additional problems. They cannot deny the relationship because archived evidence from Dongguk University's own website contradicts such denial. They cannot admit the relationship because this would trigger investigation of institutional behavior and potential criminal conduct. They cannot remain silent because international pressure continues escalating with viral exposure and embassy notifications. They cannot threaten because legal intimidation has created additional scrutiny and validated our analysis.

The response outcome analysis reveals how each option backfires strategically. Denial is contradicted by archived institutional documentation from Dongguk's official website. Legal threats indicate concern about potential investigation and provide evidence of retaliation culture. Silence allows international accountability pressure to build through continued viral exposure and diplomatic engagement. Admission would trigger formal investigation procedures that could expose systematic criminal behavior.

FACTUAL CONTRADICTIONS AND EVIDENCE PRESERVATION

Sidus's legal threats directly contradict easily verifiable evidence, undermining their credibility and strengthening the case for investigation. Their denial of facility relationships contradicts Dongguk University's official website stating that "Sidus FNH, one of the top five film production companies in Korea, is based" in the same building as the film program. Corporate identity questions arise from the discrepancy between Dongguk's reference to "Sidus FNH" and the current company's identification as "Sidus Corporation," raising legal questions about entity relationships and potential shell company arrangements.

Timeline inconsistencies further undermine corporate credibility. Previous claims of "15 years since relocation from Chungmuro Visual Media Center" contradict corporate history showing the company became SidusFNH through merger in 2005 and changed back to Sidus in 2015, making the actual timeline 10 years rather than 15. These factual contradictions suggest either deliberate misrepresentation or institutional confusion that warrants investigation.

All escalated legal threats have been archived and preserved with original Korean legal threat email including full headers and metadata, official PDF letterhead threat with metadata analysis, law firm contact information and professional standards documentation, and timeline documentation showing institutional response patterns. This comprehensive evidence preservation ensures that corporate intimidation attempts are permanently documented for legal, diplomatic, and advocacy purposes.

INTERNATIONAL PROTECTION URGENTLY NEEDED

This escalated legal intimidation campaign demonstrates corporate retaliation against accountability advocacy, systematic intimidation using professional legal threats, institutional response to international exposure, and confirmation that accountability measures are creating institutional concern. The pattern suggests awareness of serious criminal exposure that investigation might reveal.

We urgently request that relevant embassies and international organizations take immediate action to protect their own female citizens studying in Korea who remain vulnerable to systematic sexual violence through this corporate-university partnership. Immediate protective measures should include issuing safety advisories for female nationals studying at Dongguk University, conducting welfare checks on current female students in the film program, establishing emergency contact protocols for students experiencing harassment or threats, and coordinating with Korean authorities to ensure student safety during investigation proceedings.

Additionally, embassies should document this escalated intimidation as evidence of institutional response patterns, monitor for additional legal threats against accountability advocates, preserve all correspondence as evidence of systematic retaliation, and consider diplomatic intervention to protect whistleblower safety. The corporate legal threats demonstrate that the predatory system remains active and dangerous to female students who might speak out about their experiences.

Investigation support should include maintaining pressure for transparent investigation of sexual violence allegations specifically targeting foreign women students, documenting patterns of corporate-university institutional collaboration that enables systematic exploitation, supporting victim testimonies against institutional intimidation while ensuring their safety and protection, and preserving evidence of systematic institutional behavior patterns that put female students at risk. The international community's response will determine whether corporate intimidation succeeds in silencing accountability advocacy and perpetuating danger to female students, or whether transparent investigation exposes systematic criminal behavior and protects future victims.

STRATEGIC ASSESSMENT AND PROSECUTION CASE

Sidus's escalation to professional legal threats indicates several critical factors that support prosecution. International pressure effectiveness is demonstrated by institutional concern sufficient to retain legal counsel within 24 hours. Analysis accuracy is validated by institutional response patterns that confirm our assessment methodology. Investigation potential is evidenced by institutional concern regarding investigation outcomes, while accountability pressure impact is proven by corporate intimidation demonstrating campaign effectiveness.

The prosecution case is strengthened by multiple factors including easily disprovable corporate claims contradicted by archived evidence, systematic pattern of institutional behavior documented through witness accounts, corporate decline context explaining desperation driving criminal conduct, international exposure creating pressure for transparent accountability, and retaliation evidence demonstrating consciousness of guilt and cover-up culture.

Corporate panic indicators include rapid escalation to professional legal representation, formal PDF threats with confidentiality warnings, factual claims easily contradicted by archived evidence, timeline inconsistencies undermining credibility, and aggressive intimidation tactics suggesting awareness of serious criminal exposure. These factors collectively demonstrate that Sidus Corporation recognizes the serious legal jeopardy created by potential investigation of their institutional relationship and systematic behavior patterns.

CONCLUSION AND CONTINUED ADVOCACY

This escalated legal response indicates significant institutional concern regarding potential investigation outcomes and accountability measures. The rapid engagement of professional legal counsel suggests awareness of serious institutional vulnerabilities that comprehensive investigation might expose. The pattern of escalating legal intimidation demonstrates institutional recognition that international accountability pressure is creating substantial operational challenges and potential criminal exposure.

Corporate intimidation through professional legal threats will not silence accountability advocacy. We remain committed to transparency regarding institutional failures, victim support through international accountability, institutional reform to prevent future sexual violence, and international oversight of university-industry partnerships that enable systematic exploitation.

The fact that a major Korean film production company felt compelled to escalate to professional legal letterhead threats within 48 hours of our viral international campaign validates the effectiveness of accountability pressure and confirms the accuracy of our institutional analysis. Their desperate response provides perfect evidence of the institutional retaliation culture that enables sexual violence against foreign women in Korean universities.

We urge relevant authorities to investigate the systematic pattern of behavior documented in this case, including the facility-sharing arrangement that enabled predatory access to vulnerable female students, the corporate-university partnership that facilitated systematic exploitation of foreign women seeking industry connections, the institutional cover-up culture that silenced victims and enabled continued predatory behavior, and the retaliation tactics used against accountability advocates who expose threats to student safety. The evidence preserved in our documentation repository provides a comprehensive foundation for prosecution that could prevent future victimization of female students and establish accountability for systematic institutional failures that specifically target foreign women.

The urgency of this investigation cannot be overstated, as the corporate legal threats demonstrate that the predatory system remains operational and dangerous to current and future female students. Every day of delay potentially exposes additional vulnerable women to systematic sexual violence through this corporate-university partnership arrangement.

Thank you for your continued attention to this critical student safety and institutional accountability issue. The international community's response will determine whether corporate intimidation succeeds in perpetuating systematic sexual violence against foreign women students, or whether transparent investigation establishes justice for victims and protection for future female students who should be able to pursue their education without fear of predatory exploitation.

